        <name>_module_contract</name>
        <qualifiedname>dedoc.structure_constructors.concrete_structure_constructors.list_item._module_contract</qualifiedname>
        <briefdescription>
<para>\par \b Module Contract\/ \:</para>
<para>\par \b Purpose\/ \:  Define the ListItem data class that models multi-level list numbering (e.g., &quot;1.2.3)&quot; or &quot;1.2.3.&quot;) and provides ordering logic for tree construction. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>\par \b Scope\/ \:  List item identity, parent computation, lexicographic comparison. \par \b Input\/ \:  List[int] (hierarchy levels), str (end delimiter). \par \b Output\/ \:  ListItem objects with comparison and parent navigation capabilities. \par \b Links\/ \:  [USES_API(4): builtins] \par \b Invariants\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>ListItem ALWAYS stores end_type as either LIST_ITEM_POINT_END_TYPE or LIST_ITEM_BRACKET_END_TYPE.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>get_parent returns a ListItem with the last element decremented; empty if last becomes &lt;=0.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para><bold>lt</bold> returns False if end_types differ. \par \b Rationale\/ \:</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>Q: Why a custom class instead of a plain tuple? A: Multi-level list comparison requires lexicographic logic that plain tuples don&apos;t handle correctly when lists have different lengths. \par \b Changes\/ \:</para>
<para>LAST_CHANGE: [v1.0.0 – Semantic template markup and LDD logging added] \par \b Module Map\/ \:</para>
<para>CONST 3[Point end delimiter constant] =&gt; LIST_ITEM_POINT_END_TYPE CONST 3[Bracket end delimiter constant] =&gt; LIST_ITEM_BRACKET_END_TYPE CLASS 8[List item with multi-level numbering and comparison] =&gt; ListItem METHOD 5[Initialize item from level list and end type] =&gt; <bold>init</bold> METHOD 6[Compute parent item in hierarchy] =&gt; get_parent METHOD 7[Lexicographic comparison] =&gt; <bold>lt</bold> METHOD 5[Equality check] =&gt; <bold>eq</bold> METHOD 5[Inequality check] =&gt; <bold>ne</bold> METHOD 4[Check if this is the first item (level [1])] =&gt; is_first_item METHOD 4[String representation &quot;1.2.3.&quot;] =&gt; <bold>str</bold> \par \b Use Cases\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>[ListItem]: TreeConstructor → CompareListItems → DetermineHierarchyPosition </para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
